  "scenario": "On a hot tungsten wire, ammonia breaks down: 2 NH3 → N2 + 3 H2. The surface is **saturated** with NH3, so speeding it up by adding more does nothing — the reaction is **zero order**: $\\text{rate} = k$, a *constant*, with $k = 1.3\\times10^{-6}\\ \\mathrm{M\\,s^{-1}}$. The amount left falls in a **straight line**, $[\\mathrm{NH_3}] = [\\mathrm{NH_3}]_0 - kt$, so unlike an exponential decay it reaches **exactly zero** at a finite time $t = [\\mathrm{NH_3}]_0/k$. Its **half-life** is $t_{1/2} = [\\mathrm{NH_3}]_0/(2k)$ — proportional to how much is present, so as the ammonia runs low the half-life **shrinks**: the last half disappears faster than the first. The species ledger again, extent marching in time — at a steady pace that never slackens.",
